The wood is compact and fine grained, the rings of secondary tissue being developed from a normal cambium as in the case of the higher Gymnosperms, and the individual trache\'e6 have round bordered pits. There are small male cones, but the seeds are not borne in cones. They develop on special stalks on which are no scales, but a small mass of tissue at the base of the seed called the \'93collar\'94. Usually there are two young ovules, of which often only one ripens to a fleshy seed, though both may mature.\
