But no genus is so completely known as is Calamites, which will itself suffice as an illustration of the pal\'e6ozoic Equisetace\'e6. Though the genus, as was pointed out above, shows several important characters differing from those of Equisetum, and parallel to some extent to those of the pal\'e6ozoic Lycopods, yet these features are more of a physiological nature than a systematic one, and they throw no light on the origin of the family or on its connection with the other Pteridophytes. It is in the extinct family dealt with in the next chapter that we find what some consider as a clue to the solution of these problems.\
